TITLE: SpaceX Polaris launch postponed after helium leak is detected
SUMMARY: The mission was scheduled to lift off early Tuesday from NASA’s Kennedy Space Center in Florida

TITLE: Lonely dolphin may be behind series of attacks on swimmers in Japan
SUMMARY: Eighteen people have been injured this summer in a seaside town, most likely by a solitary dolphin that has been separated from its pod

TITLE: Living in this kind of neighborhood may be as beneficial as exercise, study finds
SUMMARY: More than 8,000 trees were planted in areas of South Louisville, Kentucky as part of a research trial

TITLE: Canada's wildfires last year emitted more carbon than the annual total of all but 3 countries
SUMMARY: A new study highlights the worrisome possibility that Canada’s forests might not serve as reliable long-term sinks for carbon

TITLE: SpaceX postpones the launch of private Polaris mission once again
SUMMARY: The delay this time was because of an unfavorable weather forecast off the Florida coast, where the crew would splash down at the end of the mission

TITLE: Salmon to swim freely in Klamath River for first time in a century once dams are removed
SUMMARY: The largest dam removal project in U.S. history is nearing completion

TITLE: NASA’s Perseverance rover has embarked on an ambitious road trip on Mars
SUMMARY: After more than three years exploring the floor of the crater it landed in, Perseverance has begun a monthslong trek to the rim at the top

TITLE: Their loved ones died after receiving pig organ transplants. The families have no regrets.
SUMMARY: Four people have received hearts or kidneys from pigs. Some of their relatives recount a roller coaster of hope and uncertainty

TITLE: Boeing's uncrewed Starliner capsule could return to Earth by late next week, NASA says
SUMMARY: Last week, NASA said its two astronauts who flew to the space station in the Starliner will return to Earth in a SpaceX vehicle early next year

TITLE: Experimental sensors aim to detect early signs of heatstroke and warn farmworkers
SUMMARY: An NIH-sponsored study is developing wearable biosensors that measure workers' vital signs and activity levels. Eventually, the system could alert people if they're in danger due to heat
